{"questionId":"17601","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The diagram shows the straight line <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>L</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math>. Points <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>A</mtext><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>M</mtext><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>C</mtext></math> are points on <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>L</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/4b9174a40941fe3461f6f292236df56db10b21b1.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>M</mtext></math> is the midpoint of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>AC</mtext></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Line <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>L</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> is perpendicular to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>L</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math> and passes through point <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>M</mtext></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The point <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>N</mtext><mfenced><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfenced></math> is on <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>L</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find the value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mfenced><mi>k</mi></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em> for substitution of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn></math> into their equation of normal line or substitution of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>M</mtext></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfenced></math> into equation of gradient of normal.</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<strong><em>(A1)</em>(ft)<em>(G2)</em></strong></p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Follow through from part (c).</p>\n<p><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"17601","referenceCode":"19N.2.SL.TZ0.T_2d","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Find the value of k.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"d","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 2—Functions","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.2—2d and 3d trig","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.1—Equations of straight lines, parallel and perpendicular"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}